member.name: T:IBM.XMS.IBytesMessage
member.summary: A BytesMessage object is used to send a message containing a stream of uninterpreted bytes. It inherits from the Message interface and adds a bytes message body. When the message is first created, and when clearBody is called, the body of the message is in write-only mode. After the first call to reset has been made, the message body is in read-only mode. After a message has been sent, the client that sent it can retain and modify it without affecting the message that has been sent. The same message object can be sent multiple times. When a message has been received, XMS will call reset so that the message body is in read-only mode for the client.

member.name: T:IBM.XMS.IValidationInterface
member.summary:
This is the interface used to communicate between the PropertyContext and the Provider leg. It can be used to map between formats, and also allows for validation to be dealt with.
This is not the interface that is used to deal with inner class mapping and validation within the WMQ common leg.

member.name: M:IBM.XMS.IValidationInterface.MapToCanonical(System.String,System.Object)
member.summary: Converts a key/value pair in another format to be in the canonical format which is used when inserting values into the Hashtable. We need to return both the key and the value as some conversions will alter the value depending on the format.
member.param: the key which is being converted to canonical form
the value which is being converted to canonical form
member.returns: Vector the key/value pair that has been converted. Note - the Vector will contain the key as the first element and the value as the second element. It would be neater to use a proper datatype, but this is difficult as we are communicating across packages, and the datatype would have to be public.

member.name: M:IBM.XMS.IValidationInterface.GetCanonicalKey(System.String)
member.summary: When retrieving a value, it can be given to us in any of the applicable formats. As such, we need to convert it into the correct, canonical format, which will allow us to look the value up in the Hashtable. This is in effect doing the reverse of the transformation above.
member.param: the key which we have been passed, and needs to be converted
member.returns: String the key which can be used to look up the value in the Hashtable

member.name: M:IBM.XMS.IValidationInterface.MapFromCanonical(System.String,System.Object)
member.summary:
This is used to convert from the canonical format in the Hashtable to the format we have been passed. As there may be mapping of the values depending on the format being used, we need to pass in both the key (passed in the format which we received it in - not necessarily canonical), and the value retrieved from the Hashtable.
The Provider leg can then use the key we have given to convert the value into the correct format (or leave it unchanged if there is no value mapping for the property in question).
member.param: the key which has been passed in
the value which is being converted from canonical form

member.name: M:IBM.XMS.IValidationInterface.CrossPropertyValidate
member.summary: Runs the cross-property validation checks - this asks each individual property mapper if any other properties that are relevant are correct. member.returns: String a list of failed validations (if any).

This parameter can be passed to {@link MQConnectionFactory#setCleanupLevel(int) MQConnectionFactory.setCleanupLevel(int)} to use forced cleanup. This option behaves like {@link #MQJMS_CLEANUP_STRONG JMSC.MQJMS_CLEANUP_STRONG} except that, instead of leaving messages that cannot be processed on SYSTEM.JMS.REPORT.QUEUE, all messages are removed even if an error is encountered during processing. This cleanup level cannot be used when running the cleanup utility with a cleanup interval specified, that is, it can only be used to run cleanup once, not as a repeating task.
@see MQConnectionFactory#setCleanupLevel(int)

This parameter can be passed to {@link MQConnectionFactory#setCleanupLevel(int) MQConnectionFactory.setCleanupLevel(int)} to indicate that nondurable cleanup will be used. This option behaves like {@link #MQJMS_CLEANUP_FORCE JMSC.MQJMS_CLEANUP_FORCE}. After clearing the SYSTEM.JMS.REPORT.QUEUE, it attempts to remove any remaining unconsumed messages sent to nondurable subscribers. If the queue manager's command server is running on any queue beginning SYSTEM.JMS.ND.*, messages are cleared and the queue itself might be deleted. Otherwise, only SYSTEM.JMS.ND.SUBSCRIBER.QUEUE and SYSTEM.JMS.ND.CC.SUBSCRIBER.QUEUE are cleared of messages. This cleanup level cannot be used when running the cleanup utility with a cleanup interval specified, that is, it can only be used to run cleanup once, not as a repeating task.
@see MQConnectionFactory#setCleanupLevel(int)

This parameter can be passed to {@link MQConnectionFactory#setCleanupLevel(int) MQConnectionFactory.setCleanupLevel(int)} to use safe cleanup. The cleanup thread tries to remove unconsumed subscription messages or temporary queues for failed subscriptions. This mode of cleanup does not interfere with the operation of other JMS applications.
@see MQConnectionFactory#setCleanupLevel(int)

This parameter can be passed to {@link MQConnectionFactory#setCleanupLevel(int) MQConnectionFactory.setCleanupLevel(int)} to use strong cleanup. The cleanup thread performs as {@link #MQJMS_CLEANUP_SAFE JMSC.MQJMS_CLEANUP_SAFE}, but also clears the SYSTEM.JMS.REPORT.QUEUE of any unrecognized messages. This mode of cleanup can interfere with the operation of JMS applications running with later versions of WebSphere MQ JMS. If multiple JMS applications are using the same queue manager, but using different versions of WebSphere MQ JMS, only clients using the most recent version of WebSphere MQ JMS should use this option.
@see MQConnectionFactory#setCleanupLevel(int)

member.name: F:IBM.XMS.XMSC.PROVIDER_VRMF
member.summary:
PROVIDER_VRMF property name.
This key is used to specify a specific version of a provider component required. A value of -1 can be used to indicate you are not interested in matching that part of the version information. e.g.
int[] version = {6, 4, -1, -1}; Hashmap filter = new HashMap(); filter.put(JmsConstants.PROVIDER_VRMF, version);
In this case a provider of version 6 4 0 0 or 6 4 1 3 would be suitable for return. However, a provider of version 6 3 4 5 would not be suitable. If no version is specified in the filter and a provider has two components available that both provide the same interface, then the newest of the two will be chosen.
Used when calling JmsFactoryFactory.getInstance(...)
